Germany, Year Zero
May 8 always reminds me of the year 1945. For the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandebourg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the shops in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen. The occupying armies committed all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from nothing - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, and no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate question, even though for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
For what future?
"You must help," my mother said.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food products to some distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card labeled "victim of fascism," while others displayed a Iron Cross obtained for services rendered late to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It's practically incredible, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and mainly accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the contrary, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years after, elections.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each power wanted to consolidate "its" part of Germany.
But there are nevertheless lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature and related to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy unquestionably takes root more easily in an economic revival context.
Above all, this requires initiative on the part of individuals who wish to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, the father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Hence the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey with concern for the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a way, the country ignored its past to move forward toward the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and political democracy, Germany confronted its past, with much success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other war-torn countries therefore risk confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an opportunity to look back on the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn toward the future, proud of the achievements of the last few decades and therefore filled with hope.
